\ul \ulc0 SCENARIO
\fs24 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\ulnone \

\fs30 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
My client is Tony George, a teacher of IB physics at CIS, who would like an academic accompaniment to the syllabus material in teaching students about mechanics in respect to Newton\'92s laws of gravitation and gravitational fields. The client desires an extra-curricular digital tool for purposes such as introducing a new concept to his physics students, allowing students to generate interest for the subject, and testing theories with controlled data values.
\fs24 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\
\

\fs30 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
I consulted my client in April to discuss specifically the problem at hand and develop a digital solution. The product domain was specified to a digital visualization of the effects of gravity on objects in motion on the surface of the Earth, and in the client\'92s own words, a \'93physics simulation applet\'94. Examples of similar interactive solutions for other topics were also provided for inspiration, which included simulations of magnets for Faraday\'92s Law and virtual electric circuit builders on the University of Colorado\'92s PhET website. For this particular problem, I suggested creating a simulator of the Newton\'92s Cannonball theory to demonstrate the effects of the Earth\'92s (or any massive planet\'92s) gravitational field on the trajectory of a projectile on its surface. The client thought it to be a probable idea, since it is relevant to a topic recently introduced in physics class, and proposed that there be along with the visualizations of projectiles multiple user-customizable parameters (including the radius and mass of the planet, initial velocity of the ball, and the universal gravitational constant) that can alter the trajectory.
\fs24 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\
