\fs30 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\ul PROPOSED PRODUCT
\fs24 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\ulnone \

\fs30 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The product will be a Java-based simulation of the Newton\'92s Cannonball thought experiment, meant to visualize the effects of gravitational force on the trajectories of travelling objects. The experiment is based on Isaac Newton\'92s theory of universal gravitation, which explains that any two universal bodies are attracted to each other by a force directly proportional to the product of their masses and inversely proportional to their separation. Gravity ensures that a travelling object will reach the ground as long as it stays within the Earth\'92s gravitational field, and if its initial horizontal velocity reaches or exceeds its escape velocity, it will \'91break free\'92 of the gravitational field instead of falling back to Earth.
\fs24 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\
\

\fs30 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The applet will simulate a cannonball fired tangentially to the surface of the Earth. Because the ratio of the Earth to a cannonball is realistically very large, the projectile will be treated as a point mass and the Earth as a fixed large mass. The user-input variables will include: the height from the Earth\'92s surface at which the ball is fired, the initial velocity of the ball, the radius and mass of the planet, and the universal gravitational constant. Furthermore, the user will be able to press a button to fire the ball, which will start an animation of the ball\'92s travel. Simultaneously, the ball\'92s instantaneous velocity and height above the planet\'92s surface will be displayed on screen. The animation and display values will terminate once the ball hits the planet or reaches the edge of the window.}